WEBVTT

00:00:08.039 --> 00:00:10.790
It was quite an experience for all of us to
get to hear him.

00:00:10.790 --> 00:00:17.790
And it is equally very fortunate now to have
Wayne Hale who has had a very illustrious

00:00:19.759 --> 00:00:20.790
career at NASA.

00:00:20.790 --> 00:00:27.790
Wayne came to NASA the same year I did in
1978, worked his way up as an engineer through

00:00:28.380 --> 00:00:32.409
the propulsion system, the integrated communication
systems.

00:00:32.409 --> 00:00:38.210
Became a flight director in 1988 and served
there for 15 years.

00:00:38.210 --> 00:00:45.210
He was flight director both for the orbit
phase and then the most really kind of intense

00:00:48.680 --> 00:00:51.490
flight control phase as ascent and entry.

00:00:51.490 --> 00:00:56.650
And Wayne was ascent and entry flight director
and then lead flight director for many flights,

00:00:56.650 --> 00:00:59.440
including-- we were trying to figure out before.

00:00:59.440 --> 00:01:04.049
But I think he actually served for all of
my last four flights.

00:01:04.049 --> 00:01:07.250
So we've known each other for a long time.

00:01:07.250 --> 00:01:13.010
In 2003, he was sent to the Kennedy Space
Center to be head of launch operations.

00:01:13.010 --> 00:01:17.170
But he didn't get to spend very much time
in the Florida sunshine because they asked

00:01:17.170 --> 00:01:24.170
him to come back to Houston the next year
as deputy program manager for the Space Shuttle.

00:01:24.400 --> 00:01:31.400
And then, when Bill Gerstenmeyer left to move
up to NASA headquarters, Wayne became the

00:01:31.600 --> 00:01:32.549
program manager.

00:01:32.549 --> 00:01:39.549
So he is able to talk to us both about Mission
Control operations and the current and future

00:01:41.780 --> 00:01:43.710
state of affairs of the Shuttle.

00:01:43.710 --> 00:01:49.280
And he is very happy to have you ask questions
while he is talking.

00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:51.799
And I am not going to talk anymore because
they came to hear you, Wayne.

00:01:51.799 --> 00:01:53.520
WAYNE: Thank you, Jeff.

00:01:53.520 --> 00:01:58.990
I cannot tell you how much I've been looking
forward to coming here to talk to you folks.

00:01:58.990 --> 00:02:00.990
This is my favorite subject.

00:02:00.990 --> 00:02:03.720
Space, number one.

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:04.479
The Shuttle, number two.

00:02:04.479 --> 00:02:06.330
And Mission Control, number three.

00:02:06.330 --> 00:02:11.540
Maybe not exactly in that order, but they
