00:02:27.109 --> 00:02:31.200
I will tell you all kinds of interesting stories
today, I think.

00:02:31.200 --> 00:02:35.299
Some of them might even be about Dr. Hoffman.

00:02:35.299 --> 00:02:38.519
I should tell you my background as an engineer.

00:02:38.519 --> 00:02:43.689
I got my bachelor's and master's degree in
mechanical engineering.

00:02:43.689 --> 00:02:48.840
Did not decide to pursue a doctorate degree
for a variety of reasons.

00:02:48.840 --> 00:02:53.999
You need to understand that the organization
of NASA is very much around the centers.

00:02:53.999 --> 00:03:00.999
It was organized as a group largely of independent
centers with a very thin veneer of integration

00:03:03.849 --> 00:03:05.299
at NASA headquarters.

00:03:05.299 --> 00:03:06.689
And it remains that way to this day.

00:03:06.689 --> 00:03:10.249
And every center is quite different from every
other center.

00:03:10.249 --> 00:03:13.419
We have some centers that are largely involved
in research.

00:03:13.419 --> 00:03:20.419
And, if you want to work in the research center,
Langley, Glenn, Ames then you need to clearly

00:03:23.169 --> 00:03:24.090
pursue a PhD.

00:03:24.090 --> 00:03:31.090
If you're more interested in an ops center,
Kennedy, Marshall, Johnson, then you need

00:03:31.719 --> 00:03:34.969
to kind of not go after the PhD.

00:03:34.969 --> 00:03:41.099
Because people with PhDs clearly do not have
a real world practical understanding of problems.

00:03:41.099 --> 00:03:45.529
And it is only the guys with bachelor's degrees
that get out and know how to turn wrenches

00:03:45.529 --> 00:03:48.430
in their spare time required there.

00:03:48.430 --> 00:03:50.739
So it is very interesting, the different cultures.

00:03:50.739 --> 00:03:55.269
I can say that with a grin because there are
different cultures within NASA.

00:03:55.269 --> 00:03:57.879
And working between the centers is very interesting.

00:03:57.879 --> 00:04:04.879
And since I have moved in the management ranks,
for what reason I don't understand, I have

00:04:07.309 --> 00:04:08.749
fouled up in my career.

00:04:08.749 --> 00:04:09.329
[OVERLAPPING VOICES]

00:04:09.329 --> 00:04:12.650
make you a manager when you don't get to do
the things that you're good at anymore.

00:04:12.650 --> 00:04:17.459
Yes, promote you something that you were never
trained for.

00:04:17.459 --> 00:04:22.870
It has been very interesting for me to try
to work between the various centers to help

00:04:22.870 --> 00:04:27.150
them accomplish the goals that the agency
has.

00:04:27.150 --> 00:04:33.810
One of the things I should say is that I regret
my academic career as I didn't take more psychology,

00:04:33.810 --> 00:04:35.600
more accounting.

00:04:35.600 --> 00:04:41.370
Because, frankly, when I was in graduate school,
I can remember one of the courses I had was

00:04:41.370 --> 00:04:44.720
systems of nonlinear partial differential
equations.

00:04:44.720 --> 00:04:48.409
Anybody taken a class that has a title vaguely
similar to that?

00:04:48.409 --> 00:04:50.350
I never used that class.

00:04:50.350 --> 00:04:55.159
I have never touched a differential equation
in my professional career.

00:04:55.159 --> 00:04:57.770
Now, why that is, is kind of interesting.

00:04:57.770 --> 00:05:02.370
But what I really did need was trigonometry
and accounting.

00:05:02.370 --> 00:05:05.340
And you will see a little bit of that.

