00:05:08.310 --> 00:05:13.320
It is going to be a series of illustrations
about Mission Control.

00:05:13.320 --> 00:05:15.880
And, as I said, I will be happy to talk to
you about it.

00:05:15.880 --> 00:05:22.880
I go to a lot of conferences these days, and
I frequently sit in advanced space systems

00:05:23.740 --> 00:05:24.550
sessions.

00:05:24.550 --> 00:05:31.550
I sat in a very interesting future reusable
launch vehicle session the last AIAA conference

00:05:33.520 --> 00:05:34.330
I went to.

00:05:34.330 --> 00:05:40.000
And I walked away totally distressed because
they have no concept of what the real world

00:05:40.000 --> 00:05:43.140
is like in many of these academic seminars.

00:05:43.140 --> 00:05:50.140
And I want to inject a little bit of real
world realism into what you guys think about

00:05:50.150 --> 00:05:52.080
as engineers.

00:05:52.080 --> 00:05:59.080
One of the favorite topics of people these
days that are designing advanced space systems

00:05:59.920 --> 00:06:02.890
include what they call and "austere" launch
pad.

00:06:02.890 --> 00:06:08.000
In other words, you cannot fix anything on
the rocket when it is on the launch pad.

00:06:08.000 --> 00:06:13.740
And the reason they side is look how much
money all these programs spend fixing their

00:06:13.740 --> 00:06:16.330
rocket out on the launch pad.

00:06:16.330 --> 00:06:22.250
Well, the fact of the matter is rockets are
very finicky, rockets have very little margin

00:06:22.250 --> 00:06:24.670
in many of their components and things break.

00:06:24.670 --> 00:06:30.260
They can break and you don't even know it
until you plug them all together and turn

00:06:30.260 --> 00:06:30.900
them on.

00:06:30.900 --> 00:06:37.900
And if you have a launch pad that is austere
and you can do no work on it, well, what was

00:06:38.920 --> 00:06:42.220
one of those colorful phrases that Chris Kraft
would use?

00:06:42.220 --> 00:06:44.360
You have really bought the farm.

00:06:44.360 --> 00:06:49.250
I won't use his colorful phrases.

00:06:49.250 --> 00:06:54.630
You wind up spending a lot more money because
you've got to take the rocket back to the

00:06:54.630 --> 00:06:58.680
barn and take it all apart rather than maybe
get access to fix it.

00:06:58.680 --> 00:07:02.320
If there was anything that I wish we had was
more capability to fix things on the launch

00:07:02.320 --> 00:07:02.880
pad.

00:07:02.880 --> 00:07:07.740
We spend a lot of time and money working around
problems that we cannot fix at the launch

00:07:07.740 --> 00:07:10.030
pad, even though we have a huge amount of
capability.

00:07:10.030 --> 00:07:11.180
You don't save money there.

00:07:11.180 --> 00:07:13.430
It is a false economy.

00:07:13.430 --> 00:07:18.720
Similarly, there is a notion en vogue that
you don't need a big Mission Control.

00:07:18.720 --> 00:07:24.100
That is just a lot of people that cost a lot
of money that you don't really need.

00:07:24.100 --> 00:07:31.100
I think it reached the height of the anti
Mission Control forces during the DCX program

00:07:31.810 --> 00:07:36.780
when they were very proud to proclaim their
Mission Control was a trailer house with three

00:07:36.780 --> 00:07:38.070
people in it.

00:07:38.070 --> 00:07:41.720
And they thought that was all any space vehicle
needed to have to launch.

00:07:41.720 --> 00:07:45.940
Of course, they only reached an altitude to
5000 feet and they crashed their only prototype

00:07:45.940 --> 00:07:52.159
vehicle, not because of Mission Control but
perhaps because they didn't pay enough attention

00:07:52.159 --> 00:07:54.020
to operational situations.

00:07:54.020 --> 00:07:59.520
In my business now, I can tell you that in
the Space Shuttle program Mission Control

00:07:59.520 --> 00:08:04.139
cost me less than 2% of the total budget for
the Space Shuttle program.

00:08:04.139 --> 00:08:07.150
What we get for that 2% is quite amazing.

00:08:07.150 --> 00:08:14.150
And every time the budget folks come down
from Washington to review our budget, they

00:08:14.889 --> 00:08:20.750
want to help us drive down the ops cost, they
take one look, you have the budget breakdown

00:08:20.750 --> 00:08:24.060
of the Shuttle program and they say you guys
don't spend very much on ops.

00:08:24.060 --> 00:08:27.010
This is not where we need to look if we want
to save some money.

00:08:27.010 --> 00:08:31.060
If you want to save some money, you need to
make a reusable vehicle.

00:08:31.060 --> 00:08:36.570
Reusable and not so maintenance intensive
to turn it around.

00:08:36.570 --> 00:08:38.750
And that may be a theme that you hear today.

00:08:38.750 --> 00:08:43.578
I've got a couple of things I want to pass
